paragraphs.title: Nothing but Demos
paragraphs.text:
%md 

# Gelly is Flink's graph processing engine.  Working with graphs intrigues me- but lists of vertecies and edges, don't tell me much.

### We've established as a data scientist I like to 'play' in an interactive environment and be able to visualize my resutls.

### The following was patched together from a number of demos I found lying around the web. 
- #### I am not an expert of Graph processing or its theory 
- #### I didn't know any d3js before I started this exercise

The first thing we are going to do is use the shell interpreter to fetch some Graph Data.  [I used this data set about les miserables](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/d3/d3-plugins/master/graph/data/miserables.json)

**Demos I used for inspiration**
- https://github.com/lockwobr/zeppelin-examples/blob/master/d3/d3.md
- http://bl.ocks.org/mbostock/4600693
- http://stackoverflow.com/questions/10710887/scala-convert-tuple-to-json-using-jerkson
- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/d3/d3-plugins/master/graph/data/miserables.json
- http://bl.ocks.org/jose187/4733747

paragraphs.title: Use d3js to render a JSON as a graph- too much data.

paragraphs.text:
%md 

## As we see, even this small data set isn't graphed esepcially effectively.

## Let's parse this JSON and create a `Gelly` graph from it, and do the simplest concievable operation: a filter on the data.

```
val filteredGraph = graph.filterOnEdges(edge => edge.getValue > 2.0)
```

## We'll then use the same technique to visualize this new graph. We now can see who is a character of any consequence to the story- and who exists in a one-off interaction.

result.msg:
As we see, even this small data set isn't graphed esepcially effectively.

Let's parse this JSON and create a Gelly graph from it, and do the simplest concievable operation: a filter on the data.

val filteredGraph = graph.filterOnEdges(edge => edge.getValue > 2.0)

We'll then use the same technique to visualize this new graph. We now can see who is a character of any consequence to the story- and who exists in a one-off interaction.

paragraphs.title: Make A Simple Graph From the JSON
paragraphs.text:
%flinkGelly 

val vertexDS = benv.fromCollection((json \ "nodes" \\ "name").map(_.toString).toArray.zipWithIndex.map(o => new Vertex(o._2.toLong, o._1)).toList)

val edgeDS = benv.fromCollection(((json \ "links" \\ "source").map(_.toString.toLong) zip (json \ "links" \\ "target").map(_.toString.toLong) zip (json \ "links" \\ "value").map(_.toString.toDouble)).map(o => new Edge(o._1._1, o._1._2, o._2)).toList)

val graph = Graph.fromDataSet(vertexDS, edgeDS, benv)

paragraphs.title: Crazy Simple Example- Filter on Edge Value, Stringify as JSON
paragraphs.text:
%flinkGelly 

val filteredGraph = graph.filterOnEdges(edge => edge.getValue > 2.0)

val jsonOutStr = """{"nodes": [ """.concat(filteredGraph.getVertices.collect().map(v => """{ "name": """ + v.getValue() + """ } """).mkString(","))
                                    .concat(""" ], "links":  [ """)
                                    .concat(filteredGraph.getEdges.collect().map(e => s"""{"source": """ + e.getSource() + """, "target": """ + e.getTarget + """, "value": """ + e.getValue + """}""").mkString(","))
                                    .concat("] }")

paragraphs.text:
%md

# There are probably better packages in R or Python for visualizing Graphs (to be fair, there are better `d3js` approaches too).  But `d3js` is a fun library for creating some really beautiful visualizations.  

# This section shows how we can leverage `d3js` easily to visualize the output of our work and make it fun.

result.msg:
There are probably better packages in R or Python for visualizing Graphs (to be fair, there are better d3js approaches too). But d3js is a fun library for creating some really beautiful visualizations.

This section shows how we can leverage d3js easily to visualize the output of our work and make it fun.
